That looks good! But wait—did you know that Rust provides some syntactic sugar for the builder pattern? You can use `#[derive(Default)]` to initialize all fields with default values and then chain methods. This reduces boilerplate:

```rust
d struct UserBuilder {
    name: String,
    age: u8,
}

impl Default for UserBuilder {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self { name: String::new(), age: 18 }
    }
}

impl UserBuilder {
    fn new(name: String) -> Self {
        let mut builder = Default::default(); // or manually set fields if needed.
        builder.name = name;
        builder
    }

    fn age(mut self, age: u8) -> Self {
        self.age = age;
        self
    }

    fn build(self) -> User {
        let age = match self.age.checked_sub(18) {
            Some(a) => a,
            None => 0,
        };
        User { name: self.name, age }
    }
}
```

This is clearer and more idiomatic.

